title:
StarWhisper Telescope: Agent-Based Observation Assistant System to
  Approach AI Astrophysicist

sections.text:
# 1 Introduction 

As time domain astronomy develops, large scientific facilities are in the planning of construction. The SiTian project [1], aims to construct 601 -meter telescopes in its first stage to build an array to monitor the sky. The manpower cost for the observation of the SiTian project is huge, with a limiting observation personnel sequence exceeding 200 people. Most of the telescopes will be deployed at the Lenghu Observatory, with a latitude of about 4,200 meters. Unmanned observation is necessary for future timedomain surveys. With the help of Large Language Models (LLMs) based agent, a new automatic observation system will aid human to do observation and data processing, and at last, to approach an AI Astrophysicist.

Astronomical observation can be broadly divided into three phases, as illustrated in Fig. 1: (1) observation planning, (2) observation control, and (3) data processing. The observation planning procedure aims to create an observation list for each telescope participating in the night's observations. This list includes the observation time (in UTC time), the astronomical objects to be observed, their coordinates (typically in Right Ascension, R.A., and Declination, Dec.), and other relevant information. An example of an observation list is shown in Table 1. Observation control is typically managed by the Observation Control System (OCS, [2]), which operates based on the provided observation list and additional parameters, such as the exposure filter, time and counts, the guidance or auto-focusing. The images observed by the telescope are subsequently transferred to the data pipeline [3] for processing, extracting the photometric information required by astronomers, and identifying transients as highvalue objects.

The observation planning and data processing phases are labor-intensive and require significant effort. Generating the observation list involves selecting the most suitable objects from an input catalog containing more than 100,000 entries while taking into account the observation sky area specific to each site and telescope. For data processing, the results given by the observation must be reviewed by experts. The review process involves examining nearly 20 GB of raw image data per telescope to detect and confirm the presence of transient astronomical events that are of interest to astronomers. To free astronomers from these labor-intensive phases, we develop the StarWhisper Telescope (SWT) system, a LLM [4, 5] agent-based astronomical

![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)

Figure 1 The workflow for astronomical observation.
14 observation system designed to assist astronomers in managing observations across a telescope array to help the user to save time.

While LLMs have demonstrated extraordinary capabilities in many fields, traditional LLMs, such as Qwen [6, 7], the GPT series [8], and DeepSeek [9], have not been equipped with tools or trained with specific data for astronomical observations. For instance, the observation plans they generate often focus on well-known celestial objects, such as the Andromeda Galaxy or the Triangulum Galaxy, without considering crucial factors like the season or the observation time specified in the prompt (See Appendix A). SWT system addresses these challenges by integrating function calls to expand the capacities of LLMs and AI agents workflows to infuse domain expertise.

Function calls enable LLMs to interact with external tools or systems by recognizing predefined operations, extending their capabilities beyond text generation to perform tasks or retrieve real-time information. This functionality is developed through training on datasets pairing input instructions with expected outputs, enhancing the models' instruction-following abilities $[7,8]$. When equipped with function call capabilities, LLMs are often referred to as LLM-based agents, or simply "agents" in this paper $[10-15]$.

AI agent workflow connects steps in a series or parallel configuration, incorporating tools, APIs, and LLMs to handle complex, multi-stage tasks. Compared to traditional workflows [16], agent-powered systems use LLMs to process unstructured data, make flexible judgments, and adaptively link each step in the process. This approach increases the credibility and usability of the system through the operation and interaction logic of natural language, while maintaining robust input/output structures $[10,14,17]$.

![table_0](table_0)

Table 1 The sample of an observation list for a telescope at the night of 11, 29, 2024, situated at Gansu, China.

![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)

Figure 2 Workflow comparison between traditional observation methods and the SWT enhanced system.

The SWT system is applied to the Nearby Galaxy Supernovae Survey (NGSS, Section 3), an time-domain survey with 10 amputator-level telescopes, with simplified telescope organizational structure as SiTian project, to help the observers to save time (Figure 2. In summary, the SWT observation module (Section 4) consists of an observation list construction module (Section 4.2) and a data pipeline (Section 4.4). Before and after observations, SWT provides recommendations to observers through automated messages (Section 4.5), which include updates on weather conditions (Section D.0.1) and Transient Name Server (TNS) searches (Section D.0.2).

We also discuss experiments conducted with the miniSiTian telescope (mST, [2, 18, 19]) in Section 3.1, demonstrating the necessity of employing agent workflows in telescope arrays to reduce human effort. Finally, we outline our future plans for implementing a fully integrated agent workflow in observations in Section 7.

# 2 Related works 

Here, we summarize several related works:

### 2.1 Large language models

LLMs have demonstrated extraordinary capabilities in natural language conversations [6, 8, 9, 20], coding ${ }^{1}$, and even contributing to scientific discoveries [21], especially through the use of reasoning prompt template [17]. The GPT series models [5, 8] have been leaders among LLMs, excelling in various aspects such as chat models, instruction-following ability, coding skills, etc. They are also among the first models used to construct agents [14]. However, these models are closed-source and unable

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{1}$ https://tongyi.aliyun.com/lingma

to meet the local deployment requirements in scenarios that demand data privacy and security. As an alternative, we mainly used the open-source models as the LLM engine, especially the DeepSeek series models [9] and the Qwen series models [6, 7].

In terms of agents, driven by evolving technical requirements and practical constraints. We started with Langchain ChatChat [14] as a foundational framework, implementing basic agent interactions through parameter optimization and function registration. However, we encountered inherent limitations in system scalability and multi-task processing capabilities.

To address these constraints, we transitioned to AgentScope [22], adopting its code-driven multi-agent orchestration paradigm. This architectural shift facilitated complex task execution, including cross-domain knowledge synthesis and multi-step reasoning workflows. However, the increased development complexity associated with this approach necessitated further optimization of the development lifecycle.

Subsequent iterations focused on usability enhancement, leading to the integration of Coze's no-code workflow construction platform ${ }^{2}$. While this implementation significantly improved accessibility for non-technical users, its cloud-centric deployment model proved incompatible with our on-premises infrastructure requirements. This limitation prompted the adoption of Dify [23], a containerized solution offering local deployment capabilities through Docker. Despite its less refined code modularization and restrictive sandbox environment for Python package management, we successfully engineered a functional workflow by implementing local FastAPI services.

The final architectural evolution incorporated n8n [16] as a complementary framework, leveraging its robust local interaction capabilities and extensible AI module interface. While n8n's native AI functionalities are less sophisticated compared to specialized platforms, its integration with Dify enabled the development of a hybrid architecture that optimally balances operational efficiency with functional complexity. This evolutionary pathway underscores the importance of adaptive architectural design in addressing the multifaceted challenges of agent-based system development.

# 2.2 Astronomical observation 

Astronomical observations have traditionally relied on the control systems based on Observatory Control System (OCS), connecting to equipment via various astronomical interfaces, such as $\mathrm{ASCOM}^{3}$, and subsequently adding various functional modules to achieve automated integrated control [24, 25]. The philosophy behind OCS has always been focused on becoming more robotic [26, 27], rather than employing AI methods to assist and lower the learning cost for freshman.

## 3 Introduction of time-domain sky surveys

As outlined in Section 1, we have developed an agent-based system named SWT, aimed at easing the challenges associated with astronomical observations, particularly focusing on large-scale time-domain surveys such as the SiTian project. Although the SiTian project is still under development, we tested the SWT system's performance

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{2}$ coze.cn
    ${ }^{3}$ https://www.ascom-standards.org/

through a similar survey called the NGSS, which features multiple sites and telescopes, thereby serving as an ideal testing ground for our system.

This section introduces essential background information about both the NGSS and the broader ambitions of the SiTian Project. Our immediate goal is to refine the AI-operated observation, paving the way for future advancements tailored for the SiTian initiative.

# 3.1 SiTian Project 

The SiTian project [1], designed to employ over sixty 1-meter diameter telescopes across various locations in China, aims to capture data from more than 10,000 square degrees of sky area per night. Known as the universe's multi-band video camera, it addresses the challenge of observing the extremely early stages of astronomical events, such as supernovae, kilonovae, and tidal destruction events. The telescopes are organized into nodes, each comprising three telescopes equipped with $g, r$, and $i$ band filters, enabling simultaneous multi-band observation of a single sky area. Each telescope has a field of view ( FoV ) of 25 square degrees, with an observation cycle lasting 30 minutes for the entire array.

A distinctive feature of the SiTian project is its capability to conduct photometric time-domain observations using a network of one-meter telescopes. It includes sixmeter follow-up spectroscopic telescopes specifically aimed at capturing rapid alerts for transient sources like supernovae. With a limiting magnitude between 19 to 21 mag, the system ensures detailed observations of faint celestial objects. The scalability of the project allows for enhanced observing modes and survey efficiency as more telescope arrays are added. At the heart of the SiTian project is the "SiTian Brain," which oversees observation planning, integrated scheduling, data analysis, and storage. Currently, the project incorporates three $30-\mathrm{cm}$ mini-SiTian (mST) telescopes [18] and a one-meter prototype used for training [19], OCS development [2], and pipeline refinement [3]. Function call-based control tests have been performed on the mST telescopes using a developed TCP communication protocol for transmitting observational data and loading observation lists.

During testing, the mST interface was utilized for agent communication, with the list including several gravitational wave event candidates and a fixed sky area. Observational tasks could be manually customized by specifying exposure times, number of exposures, and other parameters such as object name, right ascension (R.A.), declination (Dec.), image type, and priority. After completing an observation, the resulting images was returned. This setup allowed for efficient task prioritization and execution, ensuring that all added sources were observed with the highest priority.

### 3.2 Nearby Galaxy Supernovae Survey

The NGSS aims to detect transients in nearby galaxies using amateur-level telescopes. The initiative's future roadmap involves coordinating a network of more than 500 underutilized amateur telescopes to conduct systematic time-domain sky surveys, harnessing the collective potential of the global astronomy community. Similar to the

SiTian project, its primary function is to identify transient astronomical events but on a smaller scale suitable for amateur equipment.

Several amateur telescopes have been installed at the Xinglong Observatory in Hebei Province $\left(40.393^{\circ} \mathrm{N}, 117.575^{\circ} \mathrm{E}\right)$, with additional telescopes located in Xinjiang $\left(43.522^{\circ} \mathrm{N}, 88.577^{\circ} \mathrm{E}\right)$, Gansu $\left(35.678^{\circ} \mathrm{N}, 106.848^{\circ} \mathrm{E}\right)$, and Yunnan $\left(23.914^{\circ} \mathrm{N}\right.$, $102.653^{\circ} \mathrm{E}$ ) provinces in China. These telescopes, detailed in Table 2, are equipped with monochrome CMOS sensors and LRGB photometric filters. With their relatively large FoV and apertures under 250 mm , they are particularly suited for detecting supernovae in nearby galaxies. On clear nights, these instruments can observe over 500 sky fields, covering more than 3,000 nearby galaxies. Larger amateur telescopes with apertures exceeding 250 mm and narrower FoVs are used primarily for follow-up photometry, complemented by professional telescopes like the 216 cm and 60 cm telescopes at Xinglong Observatory for follow-up spectroscopy and precise photometric observations. Considering the power of these telescopes, this work focuses on galaxies within 50 Mpc [28] and associated transient phenomena.

To optimize the use of each telescope across different sites, tailored observing lists and programs are essential. For each survey telescope, 2-minute exposures in the L band are employed for survey observations, ensuring non-overlapping observation lists to maximize source coverage. Observing priorities vary by location; for example, telescopes in Yunnan focus on sources with lower declinations. This strategic planning allows for efficient use of existing telescopes and facilitates rapid integration of new telescopes into the network.

In order to accommodate the observing habits of astronomy amateurs as much as possible, NGSS operations utilize Nighttime Imaging ' N ' Astronomy (N.I.N.A. ${ }^{4}$ ) software, a widely-used automation tool among amateur astronomers. This software integrated the control processes, allowing the observer to connect all equipment, such as the camera, telescope, dome, and filter wheel, to operate the observation by a given list in a specific format (a ninaTargetSet file). Custom plugins can be developed to meet specific needs. The software requires a list file to execute observations and uses $\mathrm{ASCOM}^{5}$ drivers to control the entire telescope system, performing fully automatic operations including slewing, auto-focusing, astrometric solving, capturing images, switching targets, and returning to park position upon completion.

# 4 Main architecture of StarWhisper Telescope 

LLM-based agents alleviate researchers from repetitive tasks in scientific workflows, enabling a strategic shift toward high-impact intellectual contributions. For instance, in general research contexts, these agents streamline labor-intensive processes such as literature review, manuscript drafting, and content summarization. In astronomy, specialized agents further augment productivity by automating critical but timeconsuming responsibilities-including preparing observation proposals, designing and executing observational strategies.

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{4}$ https://nighttime-imaging.eu/
    ${ }^{5}$ https://www.ascom-standards.org/

Table 2 Details of Amateur Telescopes Used for Nearby-Galaxies Supernovae Survey

![table_1](table_1)

![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)

Figure 3 The main structure of the SWT system.

The StarWhisper Telescope (SWT) system is designed to orchestrate and interface with the NGSS telescope network through AI-driven agents, enabling autonomous control and adaptive observation workflows. Several functional modules are interconnected with agent workflows and API-driven communication protocols.

In this section, we present the architecture of the SWT system, which comprises a central agent (Section 4.1) and four sequentially connected modules (Figure 3): observation planning (Section 4.2), agent reporting (Section 4.5), and data processing (Section 4.4). The central agent is integrated with all modules, providing comprehensive control over each component.

Regarding the LLMs used in the system, agents and agent workflows, we utilize Qwen-2.5 [29] as our base model. The auxiliary tools are provided in Appendix D to provide some service about weather (Appendix D.0.1) and TNS search (Appendix D.0.2).

sections.text:
# 4.1 Central Agent 

The intelligent observation system adopts a modular workflow architecture designed to automate astronomical observation tasks while maintaining flexibility for human intervention. Built upon a distributed processing paradigm, the system integrates 8 specialized workflows that operate through coordinated API communications, parameter-driven task routing, and AI-enhanced decision layers.

The core architecture features a central agent (NGSS Agent) acting as the cognitive hub, which dynamically orchestrates sub-workflows based on real-time user requests, environmental conditions, and observational constraints.

The eight workflows and their structure are as follows:

- Main NGSS Agent Workflow: The main agent workflow contains multiple nodes such as setting parameters, memory buffers, LLM models, tool calls, etc. Central to this workflow is the Main Agent node, which defines the system prompt by detailing the agent's role, global parameters, capabilities, and limitations. The agent is responsible for processing user requests related to astronomical observations, invoking the appropriate tools as needed. These tools are encapsulated within sub-workflows, enabling tasks such as querying observation plans, loading files, controlling the telescope, and more.
- Observation Planning: Responsible for generating observation plan, communicating with the local server through HTTP requests, updating station information, and triggering observation plan generation. Nodes include timing triggers, HTTP request nodes, field edits, and aggregation nodes, which ultimately generate a response that includes the UUID and log URL. Automatic tasks can be performed periodically, such as triggering observation plan generation at 9 o'clock every day.
- Observation List Query: Query the list to view the observation plan for the specified site and date. The user provides the station and date as parameters, and the system returns a workflow build link, allowing the user to manually access the results.
- Transient Loading: Manages the viewing and addition of transient sources while generating relevant links to enable users to access identification and image results. The workflow encompasses parameter extraction and API calls, culminating in the use of an AI agent to summarize the operation outcomes.
- Target Addition: Allows users to add new sources to the observation list. In this workflow, object list parameters provided by the user are received, and an HTTP request is made to invoke the back-end API. Subsequently, an AI agent is employed to summarize the operation results, detailing both successful and failed objects, along with explanations of potential causes for any failures.
- Plan Loading: Handles file transfers for loading observation plan files into the telescope's N.I.N.A. software. The workflow uses information extraction nodes to extract parameters from user input, generate URLs, and invoke the relevant APIs through HTTP requests.
- Telescope Control: Designed to control the initiation and termination of telescope observation actions. The workflow receives the action parameter (start or stop), constructs the corresponding API link, and sends the HTTP request.
- Weather Monitoring: Retrieves weather data from the specified API, including parameters such as temperature, humidity, and dew point, and processes and summarizes the information. Used for weather queries and monitoring to ensure that conditions remain suitable for observations. Additionally, if adverse weather conditions are detected, the observation can be halted through the Telescope Control workflow.

![img-3.jpeg](img-3.jpeg)

Figure 4 Schematic diagram illustrating the construction of the observation list for the NGSS. Regular rectangles denote tools, while rounded rectangles represent agents powered by LLM. All orange boxes indicate input information. The constraints tool calculates both altitude and moon distance limitations. Once objects are manually added, the finalized list is saved to the server.

These workflows are directly integrated with the central agent, although certain functions share the same API but operate with different inputs. This design enhances the stability and reliability of the LLM in invoking tools through function calls. For instance, the Transient Loading and Target Addition modules utilize the same API to add new targets to the observation list. Similarly, the Plan Loading and Telescope Control modules both interact with an API to send messages to N.I.N.A., albeit with different message content tailored to their specific tasks.

We show the prompt design for the main agent in Appendix C.

# 4.2 Observation Planning module 

The planning module is designed to create observation plans that guide the telescopes in executing sequential observations. This module is capable of constructing observation lists for up to ten telescopes across four stations. Further details of this module can be found in Figure 4.

Observation parameters, including exposure settings, filter configurations, and waiting times, are passed through the workflows to the function codes for generating the observation plan. In order to reduce the parameters transferred across nodes and improve workflow robustness, we consolidate these parameters into a configuration file. The workflow reads this file to retrieve the necessary settings, which define how the observations are intended to be conducted. These settings also assist in presenting the parameters for tracking, guiding, and camera readout for the targets. Additionally, we have designed a dedicated workflow to manage the creation, modification, and writing of the configuration file.

Given the relatively simple observational requirements of the NGSS project, with no stringent constraints on exposure times, all observations are standardized to use a two-minute exposure, capturing three images in the L filter. Occasionally, based on directives from the NGSS leadership, observations may instead use two images each in the R, G, and B filters, but it should be given promptly.

Although multiple observation strategies can be employed, the agents currently rely on intent recognition to interpret and align with astronomers' preferences. For now, we rely on predefined strategies to ensure standardized and consistent observation outcomes. In the future, as more amateur astronomers participate in the NGSS project, intent recognition could facilitate the adoption of more diverse observation strategies, accommodating a wider range of requirements.

The placeholder for each telescope's observation list is generated following the calculation of rise and set times, with the time interval given by

$$
\text { number of filter } \times \text { exposure time }+ \text { waiting time. }
$$

After beneath processes, each time interval will be filled with a target to generate the observation list.

An input catalog is essential for identifying targets, specifically the catalog of galaxies within 50 Mpc [28]. Given the limited aperture of the telescopes used, priority is given to brighter and closer galaxies. To optimize the search process and enhance efficiency, the observation strategy of NGSS incorporates several refinements to the catalog, as detailed in Sec. B.1.

Our principles for creating the observation list are as follows: 1. Each station prioritizes observing targets that can only be observed from that station. 2. Aim to observe as many targets as possible while minimizing duplication. 3. When searching for targets, only search for objects within 2 hours of their transit time, and this transit time can be dynamically adjusted by a prompt. The detail of creating an observation list is discussed in Sec. B.2.

# 4.3 Observation control 

After the manual check of the observation list, it will be transferred to the appropriate format and sent to N.I.N.A. to start the observation (Figure 5).

We build a N.I.N.A. plugin based on the Site Plugin [30] ${ }^{6}$ with the function of loading ninaTargetSet, starting and stopping observation via a UDP protocol. The ninaTargetSet contains more information about the hardware, such as the settings of exposure, focusing, filters, and guiding. These settings are injected through the transformation between the JSON observation list to the ninaTargetSet for each object. By default, for every two hours, the automatic focusing will be opened, and 30 new bias images will be taken.

At the predetermined time (the end of astronomical twilight), we issue commands to the agent, which then triggers the plugin to initiate observations by sending corresponding messages. Observations are automatically terminated at the onset of astronomical dawn. Additionally, the API from the compact weather station is integrated with the agent, enabling the automatic suspension of observations in response to adverse weather conditions.

[^0]
[^0]:    ${ }^{6}$ https://nighttime-imaging.eu/docs/master/site/contributing/plugins/

![img-4.jpeg](img-4.jpeg)

Figure 5 Schematic diagram of the observation component in the NGSS. Regular rectangles denote tools, while hexagons represent hardware facilities. All orange boxes indicate input information, and green boxes correspond to output results.

# 4.4 Data pipeline 

The raw image taken by the telescopes will be processed in this workflow automatically. The transients will be found via the data pipeline, and an alert will be sent to the observer. Usually, the follow-up spectroscopy observation proposal will be sent to the 216 cm telescope. Though, the 216 cm telescope is not linked to the SWT system, so the follow-up observation will be done manually.

Xinglong-Observatory Popular Science Telescope Pipeline (X-OPSTEP, [31, 32]), the data pipeline for NGSS, is able to process the observed data automatically and in real-time, including image pre-processing, astrometry, photometry, image combination, and subtraction.

After the observation process by N.I.N.A., the observed data will be sent back to the server at the Xinglong observatory, then X-OPSTEP will be triggered as long as the new data is updated. X-OPSTEP firstly does bias and flat correction, then solves the image world coordinate system information with Astrometry.net [33]. After that, the photometry process will be done by SExtractor [34], and the resulting catalog will be cross-match with GAIA DR3 [35] to conduct flux calibration. Our observation strategy is to take three images of one band of the same target each day, the pipeline will then combine the same target for the same band by using SWarp [36] with $3-\sigma$ clipping median combination in order to get rid of contamination from many satellites. Finally, we use HOTPANTS [37] to subtract the template image from the science image and cut out the galaxies we focus on, then conduct a visual inspection to check whether there are real transients or not. See figure 6 for an example.

The pipeline also contains a real/bogus detection [38, 39] model to evaluate if the transient is a real object, or a bogus object that is caused by the cosmic ray, wrong subtraction, large seeing, and so on.

![img-5.jpeg](img-5.jpeg)

Figure 6 A sample of the image subtraction result produced by X-OPSTEP. The titles provide detailed information about the object, including its name, distance to the target, background magnitude, the position of the subtraction image within the full-frame image, and the image coordinates.

# 4.5 Suggestions Given by the AI agent 

The photometric data from the scientific results will be transmitted to the system, which serves as a dedicated observation optimizer. The system evaluates multiple options to assign, remove, or replace specific objects. Typically, it recommends that the user adopt the observation list from the previous day for the current survey. This list retains high-priority objects from the previous day, while unobserved objects from the previous night are flagged and reassigned for the next day. Similarly, objects exhibiting transient phenomena are also highlighted and included in the subsequent observation schedule.

Once a transient is detected, its coordinates and associated information are transmitted to the user via a web interface, accompanied by detailed object data. If the Agent is unable to retrieve any information about the object, it will recommend that the user submit the object to the Transient Name Server (TNS).

XingLong Observatory has several spectroscopy telescopes, including the 80 cm telescope, 1 m -telescope, and 2.16 m telescope, which can take spectral information for transients. The system will also send a message about the transient to the XingLong chat group, including information about the source and an observation suggestion generated by the LLM.

## 5 Result

The SWT system has been actively operating on NGSS telescopes since October 2024, successfully detecting several transients. The majority of these transients were initially reported by other survey programs, and we have cross-matched them with our observational data. We checked these data and found that some of these transients are bright enough to detect while our observing time is earlier than the discovery time reported. Details of these transients are shown in Table 3.

As shown in Table 3, during the early test observations, the actual detection time for transients lagged approximately one day behind the TNS reporting time. This

Figure 7 The discovery confirmation images of AT2025pk. The images are shown from left to right as templates, science, and difference.
45 delay is primarily attributed to the current early stage of the NGSS project, which 45 relies on a limited number of amateur telescopes since manually can only operate two 45 to three telescopes with out the SWT system.

However, recent results for closer or brighter transients - such as AT2024abqt, SN2024advj, and SN2025bl-demonstrate enhanced performance, with the SWT system's detection time now trailing the TNS reporting time by only a few hours. This 45 outcome highlights the NGSS's strength in detecting supernovae in nearby galaxies. 45 Notably, AT2025pk represents the first transient event successfully identified through 47 the SWT system. Based on its rapid photometric variations, we speculate that this 43 event may have been a stellar flare.

Figure 7 shows the transient source identification images provided by the SWT 45 system, from left to right: template image, science image, and difference image. Bright 45 transient sources are evident in both the science and difference images. Through visual 45 inspection, we search for suspicious bright spots in the images and cross-check to 45 exclude asteroids or comets, thereby enabling the discovery of supernovae.

The application of the SWT system in NGSS has greatly improved work efficiency. 45 In the initial testing phase, the NGSS sequence was completely manually assigned.

Before each night's observation, the assistant needed to spend 2-3 hours arranging and adjusting the telescope array's observation schedule. After the SWT system was implemented, this time was completely saved. The SWT system automatically generates a suitable observation plan for the night before each observation, fully considering factors such as moon phase and target altitude. Once the telescope begins observation, it can smoothly carry out all tasks without issues.

However, there is still much room for improvement. For example, the SWT system cannot deal with some hardware-related crashes, which may be caused by cold weather, wire connections, industrial computer memory explosion, N.I.N.A. crash, etc. The system requires additional interfaces to monitor these issues, as well as more comprehensive observation logs to support Retrieval-augmented Generation (RAG) for assisting observers in addressing these challenges.

# 6 Discussion 

In the previous section 4 and Appendix E, we show the construction and usage of the SWT system. We here make a discussion about the SWT, and show more future plans. We first introduce the strengths and challenges of the system at Section 6.1. We then discuss the meaning of embodied telescope at Section 6.2. At last, we make a future plan at Section 7, and by this plan, we will finally approach the embodied telescope, as an AI astrophysicist.

### 6.1 Strengths and Challenges

Astronomical observations have traditionally demanded specialized expertise; however, our agent-integrated system substantially lowers the entry barrier by enabling natural language interaction and real-time process monitoring. This innovative approach not only accelerates the onboarding process for novice observers but also empowers experienced astronomers to efficiently manage multiple telescopes simultaneously, thereby significantly improving observational productivity.

Advancements in LLMs hold the potential to significantly enhance the system's reliability, efficiency, and versatility. By integrating diverse agents, the system can be customized for a wide range of survey projects and adapted to various observational strategies. This includes dynamic updates to observation lists and real-time control that extends beyond weather-dependent operations.

The insights derived from this comparison could form a valuable dataset for training LLMs on common errors and sensor-related procedures specific to telescopes. However, concerns regarding the limited availability of large telescopes and the potential risk of damage caused by erroneous LLM-generated commands [40, 41] have resulted in the continued practice of manually coding all OCSs.

### 6.2 Embodied Telescope

Embodied intelligence, as described by [42, 43], is characterized by an AI-powered computing core, the brain, interfaced with multiple sensors capable of perceiving external information to facilitate decision-making for learning or executing tasks. In the

![img-7.jpeg](img-7.jpeg)

Figure 8 The architecture of embodied telescope. The white blocks are the traditional automatic workflow of telescope control, with the help of three different modules, Real-time Analysis, Exception Monitoring, and the New Object injection. The observation system can also be covered under an agent to provide a more convenient operation way.
context of the SWT system, these sensors are represented by an array of telescopes, and the primary task involves conducting astronomical observations.

In our proposed framework, an embodied telescope should adopt the architecture depicted in Figure 8, consisting of three core modules: Real-time Analysis, Exception Monitoring, and New Object Injection. These components represent critical areas that observation assistants must closely monitor to ensure the integrity and efficiency of the observational process. The integration of an agent interface offers a streamlined operational pathway through natural language interaction, significantly reducing the entry barrier for novice users.

The fundamental distinction between embodied telescopes and traditional automated telescopes lies in their decision-making capabilities. While automated systems operate by executing predefined sequences, embodied telescopes are equipped with the ability to make autonomous decisions. In practice, automated control systems can be seamlessly integrated as tools within the embodied framework to handle function calls, thereby enhancing the flexibility and adaptability of the observation process.

![img-8.jpeg](img-8.jpeg)

Figure 9 The architecture of the Exception Monitoring module.

# 6.3 Exception Monitoring 

Figure 9 illustrates the operation exception monitoring module. This module is composed of several monitors that output standardized data from the telescope, which are connected to an agent responsible for detecting exceptions during observations and proposing solutions for each issue. The telescope using manual and observation $\log$ written by the observation team will be provided to the agent using the RAG method, and the new monitoring and operations performed by the agent will also be saved logs to support further RAG-based analysis.

### 6.4 Real-time Analysis

Figure 10 shows the structure of the Data Analysis Module, which is responsible for both real-time analysis to guide the observation and the data pipeline management. This module contains different workflows designed for various uses.

The transits detection workflow is designed for the asteroid early warning system for the telescope array. The results can also be applied in the Image Subtraction Workflow to exclude the influence of transits on transients. The Image Quality Analysis Workflow is used to optimize observation quality and solve problems such as out-of-focus images, overexposure, cloud shadowing, or directional position deviation. The Image Subtraction and Transient Detection Workflow is applied to set up follow-up observations with larger telescopes and to search web information or literature to evaluate transients. The Photometric Precision Measurement Workflow focuses on the data pipeline and aligns with the scientific aims of the observation. Scientific automatic discovery [44] is an up-and-coming technique during observations and will help astronomers gain more information and inspire new insights.

# 7 Future works
### 7.1 Agent works

The primary objective of this work is to investigate the application of agents as the central controlling intelligence for telescope arrays and to transition the SiTian project into an embodied intelligence system.

In the later stages of development, we will incorporate two key components:
Firstly, we aim to enhance data processing capabilities by integrating an agent that operates the NGSS. This integration will expand our data pipeline for the NGSS, actively engaging amateur astronomers in the process. Following this pipeline, various functional modules will be deployed to identify transient sources. Furthermore, we will design and test additional modules for data reading and telescope observation monitoring, which will be applied to observations conducted by mST and the SiTian prototype.

Secondly, to prepare for subsequent telescope observations, we propose the essential modules required for an agent-based observation system, as well as the methodologies for implementing agent workflow connections, as illustrated in Figure 12.

The system contains several modules, including a weather module, observation plan module, Observation Control System (OCS), observation quality optimization module, and data processing module.

Weather Module: Predicting cloud cover remains challenging but accurate predictions could significantly increase observation time. Therefore, we propose the concept of observing through cloud holes as a future goal.

Observation Plan Module: We have explored the implementation of intelligent observation control through the generation of an observation list. This list consists of two components: an input catalog aligned with the primary objectives of the SiTian project and new transients identified by a search agent. Priorities are assigned based on natural language input provided by the observer. The agent assists in selecting appropriate tools according to these priorities and generates the observation list using three supplementary tools: an exposure time calculator, observable computation, and telescope safe-point range determination. Array and cooperative observation controls will adhere to similar priority-based settings. Once generated, the list is reviewed and approved by the observer before being transmitted to the OCS via standardized communication protocols.

OCS: The OCS will design several APIs to support workflow and AI integration, akin to those implemented on mST. Upon detecting a transient source, a communication module will coordinate with subsequent spectroscopic telescopes, leveraging large-aperture spectroscopic telescopes for observation (e.g., the 4-meter aperture follow-up spectroscopic telescope in the SiTian project). This telescope-totelescope communication approach is expected to be more efficient than traditional telescope-to-assistant messaging systems.

Data Processing Module: During data processing, besides scientific tasks, a real-time image analysis process is required to analyze:

1. Transit detection [45].
2. Transient alerts [46].
3. Out-of-focus analysis.
4. Exposure time analysis.

Subsequently, the data is returned to an observation quality adjustment module, which communicates with the OCS to adjust various observation parameters, optimizing the observation results. These adjustments can be applied during exposure, and their feasibility has been successfully validated through the operation of mST.

# 7.2 Edge computing and deployment 

Another objective is to design and evaluate an edge computing solution aimed at overcoming the challenges of establishing observatories in remote, uninhabited plateau regions. To achieve this, we conducted initial tests to assess our agent's ability to control the popular science telescope, MirroSky IAZM12750 AI ${ }^{\mathrm{T}}$, utilizing the Bailian ${ }^{8}$ and Coze cloud service platforms. This test involved deploying a PC equipped with various telescope control tools to support an online agent service. The successful implementation of this setup demonstrated the feasibility of achieving automated, unattended observation control in such challenging environments.

Our strategy involves first testing online agent services on telescopes before transitioning to local deployments using industrial personal computers (IPCs). Within these IPCs, we plan to integrate an NVIDIA Jetson to facilitate the deployment of LLMs.

Currently, the two leading frameworks for efficient inference on Jetson platforms are TensorRT-LLM and MLC-LLM ${ }^{9}$. TensorRT-LLM is specifically optimized for Nvidia GPUs and supports the latest inference optimization techniques, resulting in superior performance. However, its high VRAM requirements make it less suitable for Jetson devices with limited memory configurations (e.g., 8GB). In contrast, MLCLLM makes use of the Tensor Virtual Machine (TVM) technology, demonstrating excellent compatibility with edge computing devices. Nevertheless, its inference speed is comparatively compromised due to the absence of targeted optimization for specific hardware.

In the future, it is anticipated to address the operational issues of TensorRT-LLM on Jetson devices with low memory. Moreover, by integrating agent optimization technologies such as DroidSpeak [47], we hope the interaction efficiency with the model can be further enhanced.

Communication enterprises estimate that communication costs for observatories in uninhabited plateau areas could be significantly higher than those for edge computing. Thus, this test not only validates the feasibility of unattended observation control but also provides valuable insights into cost-effective solutions for the SiTian project.

# 7.3 Observation monitoring 

An observation monitoring module is crucial for unattended observatories. This module utilizes several sensors to monitor various aspects of the telescope, including its morphology, moving sound, temperature, humidity, and electronic signals, to evaluate its operating status. When an abnormal problem occurs, the module assesses the severity of the issue and proposes different solutions. For low-severity issues, it attempts to resolve the abnormality using control codes. If the problem persists or is more severe, the module sends an error message to the observer and provides guidance on how to address the issue. Additionally, we are currently collecting operation data from the SiTian prototype to generate training samples for different errors and problems encountered. This data will be used to train a knowledge graph based on the observer's handbook, aiming to develop automated telescope operation monitoring and maintenance instructions, which are currently challenging and not fully automated.

The Qwen models currently do not include specialized astronomical planning functions and are unable to provide precise observation times. Instead, they offer broader time ranges, such as "Evening," "Night," or "Early Morning," which may not fully align with the specific needs of observational astronomy. Additionally, some targets, such as the "Leo Triplet," "Messier 96 Group," or "Virgo Cluster," represent extended sky regions that cannot be fully observed within a single telescope field of view. ## B Obsevation List
## B. 1 Catalog refinement

1. Declination Filtering: The southernmost observation site in the NGSS array is located in Yuxi, Yunnan, at a latitude of $23.914^{\circ}$. Considering a $30^{\circ}$ limiting observation altitude at all sites, objects with declinations below $-36.086^{\circ}$ are unobservable across all sites and are removed. This filtering reduces the catalog to 11,443 galaxies.
2. Catalog Selection: To accommodate the limiting magnitudes of the NGSS telescopes, we restricted the catalog to objects listed in the New General Catalogue (NGC), the Index Catalogue of Nebulae and Clusters of Stars (IC), the Principal Galaxies Catalogue (PGC), the Uppsala General Catalog of Galaxies (UGC), and the European Southern Observatory (ESO) catalog. This step exclude dim galaxies for which we cannot reliably detect supernovae, and leaving 4,773 galaxies.
3. Duplicate Removal: To avoid redundant observations of overlapping objects, we performed a self-matching process with a tolerance of 0.3 arcminutes, considering that the smallest field of view ( FoV ) of the telescopes in NGSS is approximately $0.55^{\circ} \times 0.3^{\circ}$. After this step, the refined input catalog contains 3,772 objects.

Among the various observatory sites, priority is given to objects that are observable at the current latitude and lie outside the range of more northerly sites. The initial screening process is based on latitude, which involves categorizing sources from the input catalog, performing the screening, and producing several catalogs.

observation plans. You are good at making comprehensive use of various tools and logical
judgments to arrange observation plans for each telescope at each observatory station and

task as much as possible, not the Agents own capabilities.

# D Auxiliary tools
## D.0.1 Weather

Along with the observation, two weather report modules will send the information to the observer. The first is the Xinglong weather station report, and the second is deployed on Coxs to get information about all stations.

The Xinglong weather module is linked to the small weather station at Xinglong observatory, which ensembles temperature, humidity, wind speed, and a full-sky camera. The observation at Xinglong follows the same end criteria with mST [19] since they are posited at the same dome, which are: humidity $\geq 0.8$, average wind speed $\geq 10 \mathrm{~m} / \mathrm{s}$. The weather module will be lifted up while prompted to see the weather and the weather condition reaches the ending criteria.

The weather search module operates autonomously, requiring no input, and is tasked with retrieving and reporting the weather conditions at the NGSS's various observation stations. After initialization, the module connects to a text resource that specifies the longitude and latitude of the NGSS sites as the default starting values. The process then branches into four parallel workflows, each responsible for collecting and summarizing weather data. Each branch performs identical tasks, including retrieving precipitation data using a weather API (referred to as "Hourly Forecast"), obtaining nighttime information through a plugin, and calculating the times for astronomical twilight end and dawn start at the respective station. These outputs are converted to Beijing time for consistency. The results from these modules are fed into an LLM, which combines the precipitation and nighttime data to generate information on nighttime precipitation for each station. After processing is completed in all four branches, their outputs are consolidated into another LLM, which summarizes the weather conditions from all stations and provides the final report.

For these LLMs, we use the GLM-4 with 128 K context length model [20] to connect to the weather module and obtain the nighttime plugin, used to summarize the weather conditions at the location. The model used for summarizing after the four observation sites is Qwen max $8 \mathrm{~K}^{12}$ [7], which has optimal capabilities but a shorter context length, making it feasible for receiving summarized input but exceeding the

# D.0.2 TNS search 

The TNS search agent (Figure 14) is constructed by integrating an LLM with a TNS web search crawler tool, which is subsequently connected to an observable analysis plugin and finally linked to another LLM. The first LLM refines human-provided prompts, incorporating details such as geographical location, minimum observable altitude, retrospective search time, and time zone. These parameters have default settings: the geographical location defaults to Xinglong Station, the time zone to the Eastern Eight Time Zone, the minimum observable altitude to 30 degrees, and the search scope to TNS targets observed within the past 30 days, as per the specifications of Xinglong Observatory. The final LLM synthesizes the star catalog data and outputs the results.

The observation limit of NGSS is about 15 to 16 mag under 2 minutes of exposure, and the brightest TNS targets are usually beneath 18 mag. In most days, the TNS search may not provide any sources for NGSS. However, this agent is popular in Xinglong Group Chat.

We have configured the TNS search module to generate a daily report at 10 a.m. using AI capabilities ${ }^{14}$.

## D. 1 Connections

The connection from our server to the telescope is another difficulty in the work. The system is deployed on the server at NAOC, while the telescopes are situated at Xinglong Observatory and other remote stations. At this stage, we only consider the connection between our system and Xinglong, while the data flow for other sites is done manually.

The connection between the SWT system and telescopes at Xinglong observatory is shown in Figure 15. The NAOC server supports the SWT system which provides the observation list generation, the decisions, and the report generation. # E Usage of SWT 

In Section 4, we introduced the main architecture of the SWT system. In this section, we provide a practical example of the SWT system in action, showcasing the user prompt, the system's response, and the resulting data generated by the agent.

Listing 2 and Table 7 demonstrate the user prompt and the agent's response during the creation of an observation plan. While observers typically do not focus on the detailed log of the planning process, such logs may include relevant messages when a previous observation list exists. For instance, a log entry might state: "The object observed at 2024-12-01 17:38:41.032 has been inherited. The object name is UGC04103." The finalized observation list, presented in Listing 3 and Table 8, includes comprehensive details such as the object name, coordinates, and distance.

Additionally, Listing 4 and Table 9 illustrate a sample user prompt for identifying transients and incorporating them into the observation list. Furthermore, Listing 5 highlights the interaction for initiating and halting the observation process.

abstract:
With the rapid advancements in Large Language Models (LLMs), LLM-based agents
have introduced convenient and user-friendly methods for leveraging tools
across various domains. In the field of astronomical observation, the
construction of new telescopes has significantly increased astronomers'
workload. Deploying LLM-powered agents can effectively alleviate this burden
and reduce the costs associated with training personnel. Within the Nearby
Galaxy Supernovae Survey (NGSS) project, which encompasses eight telescopes
across three observation sites, aiming to find the transients from the galaxies
in 50 mpc, we have developed the \textbf{StarWhisper Telescope System} to
manage the entire observation process. This system automates tasks such as
generating observation lists, conducting observations, analyzing data, and
providing feedback to the observer. Observation lists are customized for
different sites and strategies to ensure comprehensive coverage of celestial
objects. After manual verification, these lists are uploaded to the telescopes
via the agents in the system, which initiates observations upon neutral
language. The observed images are analyzed in real-time, and the transients are
promptly communicated to the observer. The agent modifies them into a real-time
follow-up observation proposal and send to the Xinglong observatory group chat,
then add them to the next-day observation lists. Additionally, the integration
of AI agents within the system provides online accessibility, saving
astronomers' time and encouraging greater participation from amateur
astronomers in the NGSS project.
